d","London, England":"London, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Gedge","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of Family Names in Britain and Ireland © University of the West of England 2016","meanings":["English: nickname from Middle English  <i>gegge</i>, a derogatory term used for both men and women, though the present pronunciation, rhyming with  <i>ledge</i>, is unexplained."],"variants":[]},{"name":"James","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["form of the name borne in the New Testament by two of Christ's disciples, James son of Zebedee and James son of Alphaeus. This form comes from Late Latin <i>Iacomus</i>, a variant of <i>Iacobus</i>, Latin form of Greek <i>Iakobos</i>. This is the same name as Old Testament   Jacob   (Hebrew <i>Yaakov</i>), but for many centuries now they have been thought of in the English-speaking world as two distinct names. In Britain, <i>James</i> is a royal name that from the beginning of the 15th century onwards was associated particularly with the Scottish house of Stewart:  James I  of Scotland (  1394–1437 ; ruled  1424–37 ) was a patron of the arts and a noted poet, as well as an energetic ruler.  King James VI  of Scotland (  1566–1625 ; reigned  1567–1625 ) succeeded to the throne of England in  1603 . His grandson,  James II  of England (  1633–1701 ; reigned  1685–8 ) was a Roman Catholic, deposed in  1688  in favour of his Protestant daughter Mary and her husband William of Orange. From then on he, his son (also called James), and his grandson Charles (‘Bonnie Prince Charlie’) made various unsuccessful attempts to recover the English throne. Their supporters were known as Jacobites (from Latin <i>Iacobus</i>), and the name James became for a while particularly associated with Roman Catholicism on the one hand, and Highland opposition to the English government on the other. Nevertheless, it has since become one of the most perennially popular boys' names."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"When James Gedge was born in 1516, in Shenfield, Essex, England, United Kingdom, his father, Robert Gedge, was 26 and his mother, Margaret Bardfield, was 22. He had at least 1 daughter with Margaret Barfield. He died on 22 August 1555, in his hometown, at the age of 39, and was buried in Norfolk, England, United Kingdom."},"et":{"1516–22 Aug 1555":"1516–22. august 1555","1516–1555":"1516–1555","1521–1556":"1521–1556","1520–1550":"1520–1550","1546–1595":"1546–1595","1540–1564":"1540–1564","1490–1530":"1490–1530","1494–1539":"1494–1539","22 Aug 1555":"22. august 1555","1550":"1550","1494":"1494","1490":"1490","1546":"1546","1556":"1556","22 Jun 1546":"22. juuni 1546","1555":"1555","1521":"1521","1564":"1564","1520":"1520","1530":"1530","1540":"1540","1595":"1595","about 1530":"umbes 1530","Abt. 1540":"umbes 1540","17 Dec":"detsember 0017","1539":"1539","1516":"1516","Sheffield, Essex, England":"Shenfield, Essex, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Norfolk, England":"Norfolk, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Shenfield, Essex, England":"Shenfield, Essex, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Bishop's Stortford, Hertfordshire, England":"Bishop's Stortford, Hertfordshire, England","London, England":"London, England"},"fi":{"1516–22 Aug 1555":"1516–22. elokuuta 1555","1516–1555":"1516–1555","1521–1556":"1521–1556","1520–1550":"1520–1550","1546–1595":"1546–1595","1540–1564":"1540–1564","1490–1530":"1490–1530","1494–1539":"1494–1539","22 Aug 1555":"22. elokuuta 1555","1550":"1550","1494":"1494","1490":"1490","1546":"1546","1556":"1556","22 Jun 1546":"22. kesäkuuta 1546","1555":"1555","1521":"1521","1564":"1564","1520":"1520","1530":"1530","1540":"1540","1595":"1595","about 1530":"noin 1530","Abt. 1540":"noin 1540","17 Dec":"joulukuu 0017","1539":"1539","1516":"1516","Sheffield, Essex, England":"Shenfield, Essex, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","Norfolk, England":"Norfolk, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","Shenfield, Essex, England":"Shenfield,